        apply:      "Solve, showing full working and verifying both solutions in the original equation: (a) |4x − 5| = 11; (b) 2|x + 3| − 7 = 1; (c) |2x − 1| = x + 2. For part (c), explain why one case might produce an extraneous solution.",
        analyze:    "Analyse the equation |x + 2| = |2x − 1|. Identify the method for solving absolute-value-equals-absolute-value equations (splitting into two cases: expressions equal, and expressions opposite). Solve both cases, verify all solutions, and interpret the result geometrically as a statement about two distances on the number line.",
        evaluate:   "A student solves |3x − 6| = 2x by writing: Case 1: 3x − 6 = 2x → x = 6; Case 2: 3x − 6 = −2x → 5x = 6 → x = 6/5. The student accepts both solutions. Evaluate this work in full — substitute both solutions into the original equation, determine which is valid and which is extraneous, and identify the conceptual error that allowed the extraneous solution to pass through unchecked.",
        create:     "Design a manufacturing or measurement context (not component diameter) that requires an absolute value equation of the form |ax + b| = c where a ≠ 1 and b ≠ 0. Write the full problem specification, solve the equation, interpret both solutions in context, and modify the specification so that one of the solutions becomes physically inadmissible — explaining which domain restriction eliminates it."
